# Nagelfluh configuration
# Copy this file to config.env and edit it for your environment.
# config.env is gitignored and never committed.

# Deployment mode:
#   development         = backend and frontend run on the host machine
#   production-minikube = all services run inside Minikube as Kubernetes pods
DEPLOYMENT=development

# Minikube resources (used in both development and production-minikube)
MINIKUBE_CPUS=4
MINIKUBE_MEMORY=8192

# ── Host port publishing ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# dev/setup-minikube.sh publishes these NodePorts (and MinIO's re-mapped ports) directly on the
# host via minikube's docker driver, replacing socat/kubectl port-forward. Changing any of these
# after minikube has already been created triggers a one-time silent `minikube delete` + recreate
# (PVC data survives via the host bind-mount; docker images rebuild).
#
# host<:node> specs published on the host. Bare NodePorts map identity; MinIO's in-range
# NodePorts (30900/30901) are re-mapped back to the friendly 9000/9001 on the host.
# MINIKUBE_EXPOSE_PORTS="30080 30500 9000:30900 9001:30901"
#
# Host interface(s) the published ports bind to. 0.0.0.0 = all interfaces (LAN + localhost) —
# safe by default because MinIO/registry always require auth over TLS (see the section below).
# Use 127.0.0.1 to keep everything host-local only.
# MINIKUBE_LISTEN_ADDRESS=0.0.0.0
#
# LAN IP(s) to add to the kube-apiserver's TLS certificate SAN, so a kubeconfig connecting via
# that IP (e.g. from a second machine) passes TLS verification. Empty = apiserver is not
# exposed beyond the docker-managed localhost mapping. prod/runall-minikube.sh defaults this to
# the host's primary IP automatically.
# MINIKUBE_APISERVER_IPS=192.168.1.142
#
# Public host:port used to address the Docker registry EVERYWHERE — docker/build.sh's push,
# every cluster's image pull (including the local minikube cluster itself), and any remote
# minikube cluster registered via the "minikube" cluster type. There is no per-cluster
# addressing; one address, used consistently. Defaults to the host's primary LAN IP (same
# pattern as MINIKUBE_APISERVER_IPS above) with the registry's NodePort (30500) appended by the
# scripts that use it. Must be reachable both from this host and from any remote cluster's
# nodes. Caveat: minikube's own node must be able to route back to this host's public IP:port
# for its own push/pull (hairpin NAT) — if your router/Docker setup doesn't support that,
# override with an address minikube's node CAN reach (e.g. the host's LAN IP as seen from the
# minikube VM), rather than switching back to `minikube ip`.
#
# NOTE (app-deployment framework): in production-minikube the BACKEND and FRONTEND application
# images are now pushed to and pulled from this same registry too — not just the process-runner
# image (docs/plans/done/app-deployment-hooks.md, Design decision 4: app images go through the
# registry axis, never a shared local Docker daemon). This makes the registry load-bearing for
# app hosting itself, so on a purely-loopback setup keep REGISTRY_PUBLIC_HOST at an address the
# minikube node can still reach the host on (its LAN/bridge IP) even if you bind published ports
# to 127.0.0.1 via MINIKUBE_LISTEN_ADDRESS below.
#
# Also read directly by the backend process itself (settings.registry_public_host) to render the
# remote "minikube" cluster type's setup script (GET /static/assets/setup-minikube-remote.sh),
# which live-fetches the registry's TLS cert from REGISTRY_PUBLIC_HOST:30500 to bake into it —
# so this must be explicitly set (not left commented out) for that feature to work. See
# docs/plans/remote-cluster-provisioning-and-registry.md.
# REGISTRY_PUBLIC_HOST=192.168.1.142

# ── MinIO & registry credentials + TLS ───────────────────────────────────────
# dev/setup-minio.sh, dev/setup-registry.sh and prod/runall-minikube.sh give MinIO (9000/9001)
# and the docker registry (30500) both authentication and self-signed TLS (encrypt, skip
# server-identity verification — "Level A") so neither is ever anonymous or cleartext once
# reachable off-host. See docs/plans/done/self-signed-tls-minio-registry.md.
#
# MinIO server root account (also seeds the default StorageBackend row's admin credentials on a
# fresh DB — see the rotation caveat below). Defaults to minioadmin/minioadmin, matching the
# pre-existing hardcoded value, so a redeploy on an existing install is a no-op.
# MINIO_ROOT_USER=minioadmin
# MINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD=minioadmin
#
# CAUTION — changing MinIO credentials on an EXISTING install: the server root account and the
# default StorageBackend row's admin_access_key/admin_secret_key are the same account, seeded
# ONCE from these values by migration 182d880e84c7. Changing MINIO_ROOT_USER/PASSWORD here and
# redeploying moves the server's credentials but does NOT update the already-seeded StorageBackend
# row — provisioning will break until you also update it via the Admin > Storage panel. Hosts
# exposed on a public/LAN interface should still change these from the default.
#
# Docker registry HTTP basic auth (bcrypt htpasswd). Defaults are turnkey, like MinIO's.
# REGISTRY_USER=nagelfluh
# REGISTRY_PASSWORD=nagelfluh
#
# MinIO and the registry always get a self-signed cert from dev/setup-minio.sh /
# dev/setup-registry.sh, so the storage endpoint must be https://. STORAGE_TLS_SKIP_VERIFY makes
# the backend, job pods, and the mc/minio-client CLI skip certificate verification against that
# self-signed cert (client_kwargs["verify"]=False / --insecure / CERT_NONE) rather than failing to
# connect. This is MITM-able — only appropriate on a trusted physical LAN. Set STORAGE_ENDPOINT
# (and, if changed on an existing install, the default StorageBackend row's config.endpoint via
# the Admin > Storage panel) to https://... whenever this is true.
STORAGE_TLS_SKIP_VERIFY=true
# STORAGE_ENDPOINT=https://localhost:9000

# ── Pluggable backend bootstrap (registry / storage / cluster) ────────────────
# Nagelfluh has three pluggable-backend axes — the container registry (RegistryBackend.protocol),
# object storage (StorageBackend.protocol), and the job-running cluster (Cluster.cluster_type).
# None of the three has a protocol/provider built into core anymore — the local self-hosted stack
# (docker-v2 registry / minio storage / minikube cluster) lives entirely in the
# plugins/ymerflow-minikube plugin (see docs/plans/minikube-provisioning-plugin.md), through the
# exact same bootstrap() mechanism a cloud plugin (e.g. plugins/ymerflow-gcp's gke/gcs/gar) uses.
#
# Setting the pair below for a given axis opts that axis into the generic bootstrap() mechanism:
# `<AXIS>_CONFIG_JSON` is handed to that protocol's/provider's bootstrap(config) hook, which
# returns an enriched config to seed the default backend/cluster row with — e.g.
# plugins/ymerflow-minikube's MinikubeClusterProvider.bootstrap() starts/resizes the local Minikube
# VM itself and returns a real kubeconfig; MinioProtocolHandler/DockerV2ProtocolHandler.bootstrap()
# deploy MinIO/the registry into it. `nagelfluh-bootstrap-provision` runs on every
# dev/runall.sh / prod/runall-minikube.sh invocation — each bootstrap() is idempotent (a no-op
# once already provisioned), so leaving these set doesn't redo work on every restart. See
# docs/plans/registry-backend-hooks.md (Design decision 6) for the full design.
#
# Defaults below are what a stock local deployment (dev or production-minikube) needs — override
# only to point at a different protocol/provider (e.g. a cloud plugin's gke/gcs/gar) instead.
REGISTRY_PROTOCOL=docker-v2
REGISTRY_CONFIG_JSON={}
#
STORAGE_PROTOCOL=minio
STORAGE_CONFIG_JSON={}
#
CLUSTER_TYPE=minikube
CLUSTER_CONFIG_JSON={}
#
# To use a cloud plugin's protocol/provider instead, e.g.:
# REGISTRY_PROTOCOL=gar
# REGISTRY_CONFIG_JSON={"project_id":"my-project","location":"us-central1","repository":"nagelfluh"}
#
# STORAGE_PROTOCOL=gcs
# STORAGE_CONFIG_JSON={"project_id":"my-project","bucket_prefix":"nagelfluh-project-"}
#
# CLUSTER_TYPE=gke
# CLUSTER_CONFIG_JSON={"project_id":"my-project","location":"us-central1","cluster_name":"nagelfluh-gke"}

# ── Frontend plugin builds ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Plugin npm packages are resolved from a server-local source directory and/or the public npm
# registry, chosen by PLUGIN_NPM_SOURCE_MODE:
#   auto      (default) try the local source dir first, then the registry
#   local     local source dir ONLY — error if absent (offline / air-gapped / tests)
#   registry  npm registry ONLY — ignore the local dir
# PLUGIN_NPM_SOURCE_MODE=auto
#
# Server-local source directory the admin populates ahead of time (used in auto/local mode).
# Populate it with packed tarballs (`npm pack` produces `<name>-<version>.tgz`) or unpacked
# source directories; the build resolves `<name>@<version>` against it.
#   Example: npm pack ./my-plugin   # -> my-plugin-1.2.3.tgz, drop it in this dir
# PLUGIN_NPM_SOURCE_DIR=/var/lib/nagelfluh/plugin-npm-source
#
# npm registry used to fetch the plugin source (in registry/auto mode) AND the build toolchain /
# non-shared deps. Defaults to registry.npmjs.org; point at a private mirror for locked-down setups.
# PLUGIN_NPM_REGISTRY=https://registry.npmjs.org/

# ── Backend (server-side) plugins ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Space-separated list of backend plugins to pip-install into the backend. Each entry registers
# `nagelfluh.hooks` entry points the host discovers at runtime. An entry may be:
#   - a local path under plugins/   (e.g. plugins/billing) — installed EDITABLE; dev edits go live.
#   - a PyPI name                   (e.g. some-plugin==1.2.0)
#   - a git URL                     (e.g. git+ssh://git@github.com/org/repo.git)
# Installed by scripts/install-backend-plugins.sh — in dev from dev/runall.sh, in prod from
# backend/Dockerfile (passed through as a build-arg). Prefer the local-path form for PRIVATE plugins
# in prod so the image builds from COPY'd source instead of needing git credentials.
#
# To use local-path plugins, create a `plugins/` directory (it is gitignored), check out each
# plugin's own repo into it, and list them by path. For example:
#   mkdir -p plugins
#   git clone git@github.com:SagebrushGeoTools/Ymerflow-plugin-billing.git plugins/billing
#   BACKEND_PLUGINS="plugins/billing"
# List several space-separated, e.g. BACKEND_PLUGINS="plugins/billing plugins/other".
#
# plugins/ymerflow-minikube is the DEFAULT here because it's what registers the docker-v2/minio/
# minikube protocols the section above configures — without it, REGISTRY_PROTOCOL=docker-v2/
# STORAGE_PROTOCOL=minio/CLUSTER_TYPE=minikube above have no handler to resolve to and
# nagelfluh-bootstrap-provision fails. A stock checkout must have this plugin's own repo cloned
# into plugins/ymerflow-minikube before running dev/runall.sh or prod/runall-minikube.sh (same as
# any other local-path plugin) — see docs/plans/minikube-provisioning-plugin.md Design decision 1.
BACKEND_PLUGINS="plugins/ymerflow-minikube"

# ── Site admin bootstrap ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Seeded by a one-shot Alembic migration (e2f3a4b5c6d7), NOT checked on every startup.
# If ADMIN_USERNAME is set the FIRST TIME migrations are ever applied to this database,
# that user is created with ADMIN_PASSWORD and granted admin (is_admin=True) status. If
# the user already exists at that point, only is_admin=True is set — the password is
# never overwritten.
#
# IMPORTANT: this only works if ADMIN_USERNAME is set BEFORE migrations have ever run
# against the database. Because Alembic only runs each migration once (tracked in the
# alembic_version table), setting ADMIN_USERNAME later — after migrations have already
# been applied without it — does NOT retroactively create the admin user; the migration
# will not run again. In that case, grant admin manually (e.g. directly in the database,
# or via another existing admin through the Admin tab) or write a new migration.
#
# Admin credentials are also used for for pgAdmin and the Kubernetes
# dashboard (proxied at /pgadmin/ and /headlamp/). These are only used
# the first time runall-minikube.sh creates the
# nagelfluh-admin-secret. To rotate credentials: kubectl delete secret
# nagelfluh-admin-secret -n nagelfluh, then re-run.

# ADMIN_USERNAME=admin
# ADMIN_PASSWORD=changeme

# ── production-minikube only ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Public URL clients use to reach the app. The backend is always served at /api.
# Defaults to http://<primary-host-IP>:30080 (the frontend NodePort) if not set.
# Examples:
#   http://192.168.1.100:30080
#   https://nagelfluh.example.com
# SERVER_URL=http://192.168.1.100:30080

# APP_DOMAIN (optional). The DNS domain the app should be served at, threaded through unchanged
# into the cluster provider's expose_app() hook. It is MEANINGLESS for the core-provided cluster
# types (same-as-backend / minikube), whose expose_app() publishes a plain NodePort with no
# concept of a domain — it is ignored there. It exists purely so a plugin-provided cloud cluster
# type (whose expose_app() terminates TLS behind a managed load balancer / Ingress and needs to
# know the hostname to request a certificate for) has somewhere to read it from, WITHOUT any
# host-repo change. See docs/plans/app-deployment-hooks.md (Design decisions 2 & 6).
# APP_DOMAIN=nagelfluh.example.com

# FRONTEND_NODE_PORT (optional, production-minikube). The host NodePort the frontend is published
# on; defaults to 30080. Consumed by same-as-backend/minikube's expose_app(). Changing it also
# means updating dev/setup-minikube.sh's MINIKUBE_EXPOSE_PORTS so the host actually publishes it.
# FRONTEND_NODE_PORT=30080

# JWT secret key for signing authentication tokens.
# Generate with: python3 -c "import secrets; print(secrets.token_urlsafe(32))"
#
# In production-minikube this is now OPTIONAL: if you leave it unset, nagelfluh-deploy-app
# generates a key on the first-ever deploy and persists it in the nagelfluh-backend-secret K8s
# Secret, reusing that same value on every later redeploy (and across `minikube delete && minikube
# start`) so existing sessions/tokens stay valid — no host file (the old
# NAGELFLUH_DATA_DIR/jwt_secret_key mechanism is gone). Set it explicitly only if you need a
# specific key (e.g. shared across multiple backends); an explicit value always wins.
# JWT_SECRET_KEY=your-secret-key-here
